{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f2f44311-ba88-49eb-8dd2-acf94af623da","content":"The fastest workflow depends on your stack, but here's the general pattern:\n\n**1. Run just that one test in watch mode:**\n\n| Stack | Command |\n|-------|---------|\n| **.NET** | `dotnet watch test --filter ProcessPayment_NegativeAmount_ThrowsException` |\n| **Jest** | `npx jest --watch -t \"ProcessPayment_NegativeAmount_ThrowsException\"` |\n| **pytest** | `ptw -- -k ProcessPayment_NegativeAmount_ThrowsException` |\n| **Go** | `watchexec -e go -- go test -run ProcessPayment_NegativeAmount_ThrowsException ./...` |\n\n**Key ideas:**\n- **`watch` mode** = auto-rerun on save, no manual rebuild\n- **Filter to one test** = sub-second feedback loop\n- **Skip the full build** — watch-based test runners do incremental compilation\n\n**2. If watch isn't available**, use a tight loop:\n\n```bash\n# .NET example\ndotnet test --filter ProcessPayment_NegativeAmount_ThrowsException --no-restore\n```\n\n`--no-restore` skips NuGet restore, shaving seconds off each run.\n\nWant me to set this up for a specific project in your workspace?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c296cad0-e4e3-460a-bb7a-c2db313b151e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a general workflow tip for iterating on a failing test quickly without rebuilding each time. This is a general software engineering question, not tied to a specific codebase in the current directory. Let me give a concise answer.\n\nLet me check if there's anything in the current directory first.","outputTokens":387},"id":"da5aa663-6dbf-4f22-9114-ca699b88d32f","timestamp":"2026-04-07T15:54:20.973Z","parentId":"b50251c1-082d-4271-9942-ace1389e0105"}
